You found the issue with the Python bindings.

You’re exporting the wrong site-packages path.

Your rebuild output showed the installed UHD Python package here:

/usr/local/lib/python3.8/site-packages/uhd

But you were exporting:

/usr/local/lib/python3/site-packages
/usr/local/lib/python3/dist-packages

Those are different paths, so Python can’t find the real installed package. When you run from /workspace, Python sometimes picks up the source tree folder named uhd, which is why you saw weird behavior like:

uhd module file: None
module 'uhd' has no attribute 'usrp'

Use these exact commands

Run this in the host container:

cd /
unset PYTHONPATH
export PYTHONPATH=/usr/local/lib/python3.8/site-packages
python3 - <<'PY'
import uhd
print("uhd file:", uhd.__file__)
print("has usrp:", hasattr(uhd, "usrp"))
print("dir sample:", [x for x in dir(uhd) if not x.startswith("_")][:20])
PY

Then test the device:

cd /
unset PYTHONPATH
export PYTHONPATH=/usr/local/lib/python3.8/site-packages
python3 - <<'PY'
import uhd
args = "type=e3xx,addr=192.168.10.2"
print("Creating MultiUSRP with:", args)
try:
    usrp = uhd.usrp.MultiUSRP(args)
    print("OK:", usrp.get_mboard_name(), usrp.get_rx_num_channels())
except Exception as e:
    print("FAILED:", repr(e))
PY

Also verify the install location directly

find /usr/local/lib -path '*/site-packages/uhd' -o -path '*/dist-packages/uhd'
python3 -c "import sys; print(sys.version)"

Important rule

Do not run the Python UHD import test from inside /workspace while there is a source tree folder named uhd there.

Use:

cd /

first.

What I expect

Most likely outcomes:

* import uhd starts working once you use /usr/local/lib/python3.8/site-packages
* then uhd.usrp.MultiUSRP(...) will either work, or fail in the same way as the CLI tools
* if it still fails the same way, then we’ve fully isolated the issue to the host UHD runtime/device creation path, not Python packaging

